://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kevin_Bacon_2_SDCC_2014.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/3/33/Kevin_Bacon_2_SDCC_2014.jpg/250px-Kevin_Bacon_2_SDCC_2014.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"320" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"1916" data-file-height=3D"2454"></a><figcaption>Kevin Bacon =
in 2014</figcaption></figure>
<p>Bacon is the subject of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tri=
via" title=3D"Trivia">trivia</a> game titled "Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon", =
based on the idea that, due to his prolific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Big_screen" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Big screen">screen</a>=
 career covering a diverse range of genres, any Hollywood actor can be link=
ed to another in a handful of steps based on their association with Bacon. =
The name of the game derives from the idea of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Six_degrees_of_separation" title=3D"Six degrees of separation">=
six degrees of separation</a>. Initially, Bacon was dismayed by the game bu=
t the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_meme" title=3D"Inte=
rnet meme">meme</a> stuck; eventually, he embraced it, forming the charitab=
le initiative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SixDegrees.org" titl=
e=3D"SixDegrees.org">SixDegrees.org</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Social_networking_service" title=3D"Social networking service">soc=
ial networking service</a> intended to link people and charities to each ot=
her.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Kevin_Bacon#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The measure of proximity to Bacon has been mathematically formalized=
 as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_Degrees_of_Kevin_Bacon=
" title=3D"Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon">Bacon number</a> and can be referenc=
ed at websites including Oracle of Bacon, which is in turn based upon Wikip=
edia data (and formerly from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IMDb"=
 title=3D"IMDb">Internet Movie Database</a> data). In 2012, Google added a =
feature to their search engine, whereby searching for an actor's name follo=
wed by the words "Bacon Number" would show the ways in which that actor is =
connected to Kevin Bacon.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Bacon#cite_note-49"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
is feature is no longer active.
</p><p>A similar measurement exists in the mathematics community, where one=
 measures how far one is removed from co-writing a mathematical paper with =
the prolific and itinerant mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"Paul Erd=C5=91s">Paul Erd=C5=91s</a>. This=
 is done by means of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91=
s_number" title=3D"Erd=C5=91s number">Erd=C5=91s number</a>, which is 0 for=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"Paul Er=
d=C5=91s">Paul Erd=C5=91s</a> himself, 1 for someone who co-wrote an articl=
e with him, 2 for someone who co-wrote with someone who co-wrote with him, =
etc. People have combined the Bacon number and the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s_number" title=3D"Erd=C5=91s number">Erd=C5=91s =
number</a> to form the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s%=
E2%80%93Bacon_number" title=3D"Erd=C5=91s=E2=80=93Bacon number">Erd=C5=91s=
=E2=80=93Bacon number</a>, which is the sum of the two.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Baco=
n#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
